Bootstrap is a popular, open-source front-end framework that helps developers quickly build responsive, mobile-first websites. Developed by Twitter, Bootstrap includes pre-styled CSS and JavaScript components, such as grids, buttons, forms, modals, and navigation bars, which speed up the development process and ensure cross-browser compatibility. Bootstrap's responsive grid system and utility classes make it easier to create designs that adapt to different screen sizes, providing a consistent user experience on desktops, tablets, and mobile devices.

How Bootstrap Helps in Responsive Web Design
Grid System: Bootstrap’s grid system uses a 12-column layout with flexible classes (col-*) for different screen sizes, allowing content to be organized in responsive columns.
Responsive Utilities: Utility classes like .d-sm-none (hide on small screens) and .d-lg-block (show on large screens) allow fine control over element visibility and layout across screen sizes.
